"Pot-bound" refers to when a potted plant, usually a [[houseplant]], outgrows its pot.  Another name for this is "root-bound".  When a plant is potbound, the [[roots]] have outgrown the size of the pot.  This is easily seen, because, when the plant is pulled out of its pot with all of the soil, the roots are packed tightly around the outside of the [[soil]].  While inside the pot, the plant has no room to expand its roots.  Some plants prefer to be in this condition, and gorw better.  However, most can't grow in this condition.

If a plant is pot-bound, it should be repotted.  You would need a pot larger, by one or two sizes, to put the plant into.  More soil is needed to fill the empty space in the new pot.  repotting should be done while the plant is growing vigorously.  This is usually in the spring.  Soil for the repotting should not be taken from oudoors since this can introduce bugs.  Some plants however, grow too large in order to be repotted.  When a plant is too large, it is difficult to lift.  Attempting to repot very large plants can cause injury to both the plant and the person.  Instead, fresh potting soil should be spread over the surface of the existing soil the pot contains.

